  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2729009052" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2729009052" />
    <a title="Alex Sarll" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5866774-alex-sarll"><img alt="Alex Sarll" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1453246877p2/5866774.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2729009052?book_show_action=true">Mar 12, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Alex Sarll" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Alex Sarll" href="/user/show/5866774-alex-sarll">Alex Sarll</a>
      </span>

          added it


          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/24832938-the-march-of-folly">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2729009052" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer13504557889822567427">A magnificent, astringent and idiosyncratic work of history which I&apos;ve owned for the best part of three years, and there&apos;s no particular reason I&apos;m reading it now, honest. It looks chiefly at four famous examples of folly, defined as a policy which &apos;must have been perceived as counter-productive in its own time, not merely by hindsight&apos;; equally, &apos;a feasible alternative course of action must have been available&apos;. The third rule is that it must persist beyond one political lifetime, but little pr</span>
  <span id="freeText13504557889822567427" style="display:none">A magnificent, astringent and idiosyncratic work of history which I've owned for the best part of three years, and there's no particular reason I'm reading it now, honest. It looks chiefly at four famous examples of folly, defined as a policy which 'must have been perceived as counter-productive in its own time, not merely by hindsight'; equally, 'a feasible alternative course of action must have been available'. The third rule is that it must persist beyond one political lifetime, but little pretence is made of adhering to this; I think it's intended more to separate the sort of folly in which she's interested, the sort requiring complicity and groupthink, from the whim of a lone despot. The main case studies are the fall of Troy; the Reformation in terms of the Papal failings which bolstered it; Britain's loss of the American colonies; and, in the book's last and longest section, the Vietnam War. But an introduction sketches various other contenders, from Rehoboam and Jeroboam, through Germany's resumption of unrestricted submarine warfare, to the attack on Pearl Harbor. You might object that at least two of these examples only debatably belong to the province of the historian, being more a matter of myth, at least as they're commonly understood. Still, I think the idea is that they've been accepted as true for long enough that they offer valuable examples of trends in human foolishness. Besides, without them you'd lose a Hell of a callback when it comes to Laocoon.<br /><br />In this anatomy of folly, one key concept is wooden-headedness, which 'consists in assessing a situation in terms of preconceived fixed notions while ignoring or rejecting any contrary signs. It is acting according to wish while not allowing oneself to be deflected by the facts. It is epitomized in a historian's statement about Philip II of Spain, the surpassing wooden-head of all sovereigns: "No experience of the failure of his policy could shake his belief in its essential excellence."'<br /><br />OK, maybe there was a reason I ended up reading this when I did.<br /><br />Seriously, I was just clearing out my 'phone ahead of this review and there were about 20 screenshots of quotes, which especially regarding the War of Independence chapter, could almost all have been annotated "a bit like Brexit, aaaaah":<br />- 'George Meredith wrote in a very different context of "drifting into vanities, congregating in absurdities, planning short-sightedly, plotting dementedly"'.<br />- Lord North would occasionally beg the King to be allowed to resign, insisting that the Prime Minister should be "a man of great abilities, and who is confident of his abilities, who can choose decisively, and carry his determination authoratively into execution...and be capable of forming wise plans and of combining and connecting the whole force and operations of givernment. I am certainly not such a man." Remind you of any other PMs we might know? See also 'Lord North, averse to the definitive, was trying to delay anything irreversible', or demanding ahead of a parley red lines which render it impossible to make any progress.<br />- Britain betrayed into foolish actions "by the arts of imposition, by its own credulity, through the means of false hope, false pride and promised advantages of the most romantic and improbable nature'.<br />- And if North is May, Charles Townshend must be Boris, smarter than most of his peers, but unscrupulous, unreliable, and in the end not nearly as smart as he thinks he is.<br />- Britain's politicians sharing a sense of superiority which leads to ignorance because it suppresses curiosity. Well, thank goodness the last 250 years diversified the composition of Parliament, right? Just a shame it was so very slightly. 'They entered young, were rarely prepaared or trained for the tasks, could become restless or bored under difficulties and usually retreated for half the year to the charms of their country homes'. Or indeed, their writing sheds.<br />- 'An independent member, Sir William Meredith, found the Government "so perversely, so inflexibly persisting in error on every occasion" as to cause surprise, in Dryden's phrase, "that 'they never deviate into sense' nor stumble upon propriety by downright accident."'<br />- Britain, in the words of one understandably baffled contemporary observer, "only invented occasionally some miserable tale for the day in order meanly to sneak out of difficulties into which they had proudly strutted... By such management, by the irresistible operation of feeble councils...they have shaken the pillars of commercial empire that circled the globe."<br />- Of the futile assertion of authority and sovereignty which cannot be exercised: "They tell you that your dignity is tied to it... This dignity is a terrible encumbrance to you for it has of late been ever at war with your interest, your equity and every idea of your policy."<br />- "The parliamentary cabals, being mere struggles for favour and power, created more real blood and personal rancour between individuals than the great questions of policy and principle."<br />- Britain, constantly 'asserting a right you know you cannot exert', gradually coming to be seen 'as both despotic in intent and ineffectual in execution'. Coincidentally, those were also the design specs for Gavin Williamson.<br /><br />And there's plenty more where those came from. Not that spotting the horribly applicable prophecies of doom is the only charm. Tuchman displays a beautifully and coldly savage way with words throughout – 'In between flashes of good government, folly has its day. In the Bourbons of France, it burst into brilliant flower.' – and is happy to admit when her field runs up against the limits of human attention. Of Renaissance Italy's baffling period of intercity plot and counterplot - 'The significance of the particulars in history's permanent annals is virtualy nil except as a study in the human capacity for conflict'. Which is deeply reassuring as a 'so it's not just me!' moment for any reader who's struggled to remember which statelet was doing what to whom at any given time, even while reading about it. Despite which, the larger-than-life depravity of the Borgias et al renders the Reformation section by far the most fun – how could it not be when you have things like the Petrucci conspiracy to poison the Pope's arse? Long thought confected, and at the time of writing only recently revealed as probably real, it sounds like something from the George RR Martin reboot of Father Ted. Though at times the reputation of the Renaissance Popes does seem a little unfair when you look at their heirs. In those innocent days, the notorious Alexander VI was frowned upon not for all the shagging per se, but because shagging someone 40 years younger than him was felt to be a bit off. Whereas I was reading that on the day a former Vatican treasurer was finally found guilty of, imagine our surprise, raping choirboys. The age difference there, perfectly, being one year more than that scandalous gap between Rodrigo Borgia and his lover - who was not only willing but, at 19, pretty much a dried-up old spinster in the eye of the average modern priest.<br /><br />As for the Vietnam chapter, the recurring note there is of American generals and politicians making entirely sensible policy statements, which their subsequent actions completely ignore, so I suppose the closest modern comparison for that one would probably be global warming (at least until the last couple of years, when we stopped getting even the sensible if empty verbiage). Far less anti-American and far more anti-communist than is now generally fashionable, this was also the section where I was finding out the most wholly new information, rather than having it arranged for me in illuminating new patterns*. Perhaps this is a generational thing, but in the UK I'm not sure we really get more about Vietnam than that it was a bloody mess which we were well out of, with a few big films filling in the micro detail of that, but never really the macro detail of why the blazes it happened at all. And I tried the Ken Burns show, but concluded that ten hours was possibly a bit more explanation that I needed. The three hours here, though? Ideal. This is also the section most obviously intended as a warning from (then pretty recent) history, but honestly, the whole book reads like a twentieth century Cassandra. When Tuchman talks about rulers misled by the 'illusion of permanence, of the inviolabity of their power and their status'; about how America's system has always succeeded in righting itself though 'Under accelerating incompetence in America, this may change', particularly when paired with a greater shortage of resources...they were sensible enough warnings in 1984, when this was first published, and wouldn't it have been lovely had someone bloody listened, so that they weren't still more relevant and urgent today? Leaving us to cling to a few faint shards of hope. After all, most of these errors were reversed in the end, albeit with far more loss of life and prestige than had error been admitted and courses corrected far sooner. And the worst predictions were generally as off the mark as the earlier assumptions of easy victory had been: Shelburne was wrong to forecast that, with the loss of America, Britain "shall be reduced to a miserable little island, and from a mighty empire sink into as insignificant a country as Denmark or Sardinia!" When Communism conquered the whole of Vietnam, only a few further dominoes fell, and America did not lose the Pacific. Hell, even the Catholic Church persists, somehow, though I do wish it wouldn't. The Earth, for all that it may continue generally to be run by idiots, has abided thus far, even if it does keep justifying its ancient designation as the Meadow of Atë, goddess of folly.<br /><br />*An example: I had already known, because how could I not, that the road to that fateful tax on American tea began after the abandonment of an attempt to tax cider which had aroused the monumental intransigence of the West Country. What I had not realised was that the Chancellor of the Exchequer who quailed was our old friend Sir Francis Dashwood, of Hellfire Club fame. Good lad.</span>
  <a data-text-id="13504557889822567427" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


