<div id="review_3782593970" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3782593970" />
    <a title="Brian Schimmoller" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/108762821-brian-schimmoller"><img alt="Brian Schimmoller" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/u_50x66-632230dc9882b4352d753eedf9396530.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3782593970?book_show_action=true">Jan 19, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Brian Schimmoller" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Brian Schimmoller" href="/user/show/108762821-brian-schimmoller">Brian Schimmoller</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3782593970" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4022643844071949850">History is rife with lessons, but it’s rare to see such lessons stitched together across such disparate events as the Trojan Horse, the Papal States, the American Evolution, and the Vietnam War. But Barbara Tuchman does a phenomenal job of relating history in a way that shows how “human” history is, and how susceptible we all are to unconscious and ultimately damaging biases. Folly is never more than a few bad decisions away. While it might be argued that Tuchman has the academic benefit of 20/2</span>
  <span id="freeText4022643844071949850" style="display:none">History is rife with lessons, but it’s rare to see such lessons stitched together across such disparate events as the Trojan Horse, the Papal States, the American Evolution, and the Vietnam War. But Barbara Tuchman does a phenomenal job of relating history in a way that shows how “human” history is, and how susceptible we all are to unconscious and ultimately damaging biases. Folly is never more than a few bad decisions away. While it might be argued that Tuchman has the academic benefit of 20/20 hindsight, that doesn’t diminish the impact of her cautionary tales. My only critique would be that the depth of her knowledge is such that the lay reader may lose track of characters and events at times. Sadly, but perhaps not surprisingly, many more examples of folly can be recognized in world events since the publication of this book in 1984.</span>
  <a data-text-id="4022643844071949850" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


